⭐ Creating a Virtual Machine Using Oracle VirtualBox
➤ Step 1: Install Oracle VirtualBox

• Download Oracle VirtualBox from the official website: https://www.virtualbox.org

• Run the installer file
• Follow the installation wizard and complete the setup
• Launch VirtualBox after installation

➤ Step 2: Start Creating a New Linux Virtual Machine

• Open VirtualBox and click “New”
• Enter the name of the VM (Example: Ubuntu-VM)
• Select Type: Linux
• Select Version: Ubuntu (64-bit) or CentOS (64-bit)
• Click Next

➤ Step 3: Allocate Memory (RAM)

• Choose the amount of RAM for the VM (Recommended: 2GB – 4GB)
• Click Next

➤ Step 4: Create a Virtual Hard Disk

• Choose Create a virtual hard disk now
• Select VDI (VirtualBox Disk Image)
• Choose Dynamically allocated
• Set the disk size (Recommended: 20GB or more)
• Click Create

➤ Step 5: Attach the Linux ISO Image

• Select the newly created VM from the left panel
• Click Settings → Storage
• Under “Controller: IDE”, click the empty disk icon
• Click Choose a disk file
• Select the downloaded Linux ISO file (Ubuntu/CentOS)
• Click OK

➤ Step 6: Start the VM and Begin Installation

• Click Start
• The VM will boot using the ISO file
• Select Install Ubuntu or Install CentOS
• Follow the installation steps:
– Choose language
– Set keyboard layout
– Create user account
– Select installation type
– Complete installation

➤ Step 7: Observe Boot Process

• After installation, restart the VM
• The Linux OS will boot from the virtual hard drive
• Login to the desktop screen

➤ Step 8: Capture Screenshots

• Take screenshots of:
– VirtualBox main window
– VM creation steps
– ISO selection
– Linux installation screens
– Final booted desktop
